	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU farmers concerned at growing level of imports of fruit and vegetables</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 21 July, the UK National Farmers’ Union (NFU) President Peter Kendall described as ‘short sighted’ and ‘deeply flawed’ the growing reliance of European consumers on imported fruit and vegetables. This followed the release of a study by Humboldt University Berlin on the impact of agricultural imports on land utilisation outside the EU, which revealed that the EU relies on 34.9 million ‘virtual’ hectares of arable land in 2007/08 to meet its food import needs (equivalent to about double the agricultural land area of the UK). Approximately 7.8% of this is accounted for by fruit and vegetable imports. Mr Kendall called for urgent action to reverse the decline in EU fruit and vegetable production, calling specifically for the maintenance of public support to scientific and applied technology research in the face of government budget cutbacks.</p><p>Meanwhile, in the context of new EU rules on aid for fruit and vegetable producer organisations, Copa-Cogeca has called for the EU Council to ‘make sure that producer organisations, which are engaged in the primary processing of fruit and vegetables, are fully supported in their efforts to enable producers to have a fairer share of the retail price.’ This follows a recent assessment that procedural rule changes may result in a reduction of publicly financed aid to producer organisations involved in value-added processing of fruit and vegetable products. In Copa-Cogeca’s view, this needs to be seen against the background of ‘the huge buying power of a handful of processors and supermarkets’, as they note that the farmer’s share of the retail price has fallen from 31% ten years ago to 24% today.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>farmersguardian.com</i>, ‘EU food security is “deeply flawed”’, 22 July 2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://www.farmersguardian.com/home/arable/arable-news/eu-food-security-is-%E2%80%98deeply-flawed%E2%80%99/33273.article" target="_self">http://www.farmersguardian.com/home/arable/arable-news/eu-food-security-...</a></p><p>OPERA research centre, blog, ‘Is the EU the largest net importer of agricultural produce and “virtual” land?’, 26 May 2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://irishseedsavers.digino.virtual.tibus.net/research/2010/genetic-modification/land-grabbing-is-the-eu-the-largest-net-importer-of-agricultural-produce-and-%E2%80%98virtual%E2%80%99-land/" target="_self">http://irishseedsavers.digino.virtual.tibus.net/research/2010/genetic-mo...</a></p><p>Humboldt University Berlin, summary, ‘Can more efficiency prevent increasing “land grabbing” outside of Europe?’, April 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.denkgroot.nu/pdf/Can_More_Efficiency_Prevent_Increasing_%27Land-Grabbing%27_Outside_Of_Europe%27.pdf" target="_self">http://www.denkgroot.nu/pdf/Can_More_Efficiency_Prevent_Increasing_%27La...</a></p><p>Humboldt University Berlin, research report, ‘EU agricultural production and trade: can more efficiency prevent increasing “land-grabbing” outside of Europe?’, undated</p><p>
<a href="http://www.agripol.de/Final_Report_100505_Opera.pdf" target="_self">http://www.agripol.de/Final_Report_100505_Opera.pdf</a></p><p>Copa-Cogeca, point of access to press releases, 15 July 2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://www.copa-cogeca.be/Main.aspx?page=Archive&amp;lang=en" target="_self">http://www.copa-cogeca.be/Main.aspx?page=Archive&amp;lang=en</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Efforts by farmers’ organisation to promote greater procurement of EU-produced fruit and vegetables are unlikely to be restricted to maintaining budgets for scientific and applied technology research. They are also likely to focus on promoting the stricter application of quota controls under bilateral trade agreements with non-ACP countries and the more rigorous application of SPS and food safety controls. While developments in the former area could aid ACP suppliers by supporting EU market prices, developments in SPS and food-safety controls could increase the costs of exporting to the EU for ACP fruit and vegetable exporters.</p><p>However there is also an opposite trend apparent. In July 2010, administrative measures were introduced in the UK, through the Assured Importer Scheme, to reduce checks on reputable traders which have an established track record for meeting high SPS, food safety and quality standards (e.g. via compliance with GLOBALGAP standards), thereby facilitating imports of horticultural products subject to specific marketing standards. It is therefore unclear to what extent farmer pressure to restrict trade on SPS and food safety grounds will in fact be taken up by the European Commission services. The further development of initiatives such as the Assured Importer Scheme, in the context of an intensification of ACP-EU dialogue on ensuring a development-friendly implementation of SPS and food safety controls, could contribute to significant cost savings, not only for EU importers but potentially also for ACP exporters.</p><p>Against this background, EU policy initiatives to strengthen the position of EU producer organisations and improve the functioning of the fruit and vegetable supply chain, could well come to have a greater commercial impact on the relative position of EU and ACP suppliers in the marketplace. This suggests that ACP producers and exporters may need to pay increased attention to EU policy developments in these areas.</p>
		</div>
		
